05507nam a2200709Ia 9780292796775DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20102005txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927967757 a10.7560/7065902doi  a(DE-B1597)587253  a(OCoLC)1286806439  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a623.7100aMapping and Empire :bSoldier-Engineers on the Southwestern Frontier /ced. by Gerald D. Saxon, Dennis Reinhartz. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2010] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOne. Spanish Maritime Charting of the Gulf of Mexico and the California Coast -- tTwo. Spanish Military Engineers in the New World before 1750 -- tThree. Spanish Military Mapping of the Northern Borderlands after 1750 -- tFour. U.S. Army Military Mapping of the American Southwest during the Nineteenth Century -- tFive. Henry Washington Benham: A U.S. Army Engineer’s View of the U.S.-Mexican War -- tSix. Trabajos Desconocidos, Ingenieros Olvidados: Unknown Works and Forgotten Engineers of the Mexican Boundary Commission -- tSeven. Soldier-Engineers in the Geographic Understanding of the Southwestern Frontier: An Afterthought -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the sixteenth through the mid-nineteenth centuries, Spain, then Mexico, and finally the United States took ownership of the land from the Gulf Coast of Texas and Mexico to the Pacific Coast of Alta and Baja California—today's American Southwest. Each country faced the challenge of holding on to territory that was poorly known and sparsely settled, and each responded by sending out military mapping expeditions to set boundaries and chart topographical features. All three countries recognized that turning terra incognita into clearly delineated political units was a key step in empire building, as vital to their national interest as the activities of the missionaries, civilian officials, settlers, and adventurers who followed in the footsteps of the soldier-engineers. With essays by eight leading historians, this book offers the most current and comprehensive overview of the processes by which Spanish, Mexican, and U.S. soldier-engineers mapped the southwestern frontier, as well as the local and even geopolitical consequences of their mapping. Three essays focus on Spanish efforts to map the Gulf and Pacific Coasts, to chart the inland Southwest, and to define and defend its boundaries against English, French, Russian, and American incursions. Subsequent essays investigate the role that mapping played both in Mexico's attempts to maintain control of its northern territory and in the United States' push to expand its political boundary to the Pacific Ocean. The concluding essay draws connections between mapping in the Southwest and the geopolitical history of the Americas and Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aMilitary mapsxHistory. 0aMilitary topographyzSouthwestern StatesxHistory. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBuisseret, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEhrenberg, Ralph E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrancaviglia, Richard V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHébert, John R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMathes, W. Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRebert, Paula, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReinhartz, Dennis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu